%I A393939 #13 Mar 20 2026 00:01:58
%S A393939 1,1,1,4,5,18,33,67,82,129,190,278,365,450,483,479,455,422,356,284,
%T A393939 208,138,72,28,8,1,1235,469,118,21,2
%N A393939 Number of free polycubes with n cells such that pairs of cell centers determine the largest possible number (A394394(n)) of distinct lines.
%C A393939 For 1 <= n <= 26, a(n) is the number of free polycubes with n cells and no 3 collinear cell centers, i.e., pairs of cell centers determine n*(n-1)/2 distinct lines. No such polycube exists for n > 26.
%C A393939 For 27 <= n <= 31, a(n) is the number of free polycubes with 3 cell centers on a line but no other collinearities, i.e., pairs of cell centers determine n*(n-1)/2-2 distinct lines. No such polycube exists for n > 31.
%C A393939 The unique free polycube with 26 cells and no 3 collinear cells (see linked illustration): {(0,1,2), (0,1,3), (0,2,1), (0,2,2), (1,0,3), (1,1,3), (1,1,4), (1,2,1), (1,2,4), (1,3,1), (1,3,2), (1,4,2), (2,0,2), (2,0,3), (2,1,0), (2,1,1), (2,2,4), (2,2,5), (2,3,3), (2,3,4), (3,0,2), (3,1,1), (3,1,2), (3,2,3), (3,3,3), (4,2,3)}.
%H A393939 Pontus von Brömssen, <a href="/A393939/a393939.gif">Illustration of the unique free polycube with 26 cells and no 3 collinear cells</a>.
%H A393939 <a href="/index/Pol#polyominoes">Index entries for sequences related to polyominoes</a>.
%F A393939 a(n) = A393938(n,1) + A393938(n,2) for 1 <= n <= 26.
%Y A393939 Cf. A038119, A378169, A393938, A394392 (polyominoes), A394394, A394395 (distinct directions of lines).
%K A393939 nonn,more,changed
%O A393939 1,4
%A A393939 _Pontus von Brömssen_, Mar 04 2026
